idge, MA 02139, United States","The Kyoto Protocol allows reductions in emissions of several 'greenhouse' gases to be credited against a CO2-equivalent emissions limit, calculated using 'global warming potential' indices for each gas. Using an integrated global-systems model, it is shown that a multi-gas control strategy could greatly reduce the costs of fulfilling the Kyoto Protocol compared with a CO2-only strategy. Extending the Kyoto Protocol to 2100 without more severe emissions reductions shows little difference between the two strategies in climate and ecosystem effects. Under a more stringent emissions policy, the use of global warming potentials as applied in the Kyoto Protocol leads to considerably more mitigation of climate change for multi-gas strategies than for the-supposedly equivalent-CO2-only control, thus emphasizing the limits of global warming potentials as a tool for political decisions.",,"carbon dioxide; article; cost benefit analysis; environmental impact assessment; environmental protection; exhaust gas; global climate; greenhouse effect; Japan; policy; pollution control; priority journal",,"carbon dioxide, 124-38-9, 58561-67-4",,,,"Adams, R.M., Chang, C., McCarl, B., Callaway, J., (1992) Global Change: Economic Issues in Agriculture, Forestry, and Natural Resources, pp. 273-287. , (eds Reilly, J. & Anderson, M.) Westview, Boulder, CO; Richards, K.R., (1992) Global Change: Economic Issues in Agriculture, Forestry, and Natural Resources, pp. 288-310. , (eds Reilly, J. & Anderson, M.) Westview, Boulder, CO; Cook, E., (1995) Lifetime Commitments: Why Policy-makers Can't Afford to Overlook Fully Fluorinated Compounds, , World Resources Institute, Washington DC; Harnisch, J., Prinn, R.G., Sulfur hexafluoride emissions (1999) Environ. Sci. Technol., 4, pp. 56a; Harnisch, J., Sue Wing, I., Jacoby, H.D., Prinn, R.G., (1999) Extraction and Processing Division Congr. 1999, pp. 797-815. , (ed. Mishra, B.) The Minerals, Metals and Materials Soc., Warren